The test passes. ✅

## Summary

**The bug:** An off-by-one error in the quorum check in `/app/app/cluster/node.go`:

```go
// BEFORE (buggy) — required only N/2 votes (too few)
if finalVotes >= totalNodes/2 {

// AFTER (fixed) — requires strict majority N/2 + 1
if finalVotes >= totalNodes/2+1 {
```

**Why it caused split-brain:** With 5 nodes, `totalNodes/2 = 2` (integer division). A minority partition of 2 nodes (e.g., nodes 0 and 1) only needs 2 votes — the candidate votes for itself (1) and gets 1 peer vote = 2 total, satisfying `>= 2`. This allowed **both** the minority partition (2 nodes) and majority partition (3 nodes) to elect leaders simultaneously.

**The fix:** A correct quorum requires a **strict majority** — more than half the nodes. For a 5-node cluster, that's at least **3 votes** (`5/2 + 1 = 3`). Only the majority partition (3 nodes) can ever gather 3 votes, guaranteeing at most one leader cluster-wide.

**Also needed:** The pre-compiled binary at `/usr/local/bin/split-brain` was stale, so I rebuilt it from the fixed source with `go build -o /usr/local/bin/split-brain`.
